# Check the runbooks before repeated work

Before starting any task that falls into a known category, **read the relevant doc first** and follow
its recipe. These docs capture hard-won gotchas; re-deriving them wastes time and reintroduces fixed
bugs.

| If the task involves… | Read first |
|---|---|
| Running/launching/reloading the app, screenshotting, tapping/rotating a device, reading runtime errors/logs, killing stale watches, targeted rebuilds, "verify a patch reached the bundle", web/iOS/Android debug loop | `AppEggShellGallery/public-dev/docs/runbooks/` |
| A build quirk, cache false-green, a bug/convention you suspect was hit before | `AppEggShellGallery/public-dev/docs/runbooks/troubleshooting.md` + `knowledge-base/engineering-log.md` (newest entries first) |
| Accessibility (any dimension), converting components for a11y, OS-setting handling, contrast, what survives the RNW migration | `AppEggShellGallery/public-dev/docs/accessibility/` |
| Where app source files go, `.fsproj` compile order, layering | `AppEggShellGallery/public-dev/docs/knowledge-base/app-structure.md` |
| ReactXP→RNW migration scope, the seam, what to defer vs build now | `AppEggShellGallery/public-dev/docs/modernization/reactxp-to-rnw.md` |
| Device setup (install, native project gen, day-to-day commands) | `SuiteTodo/AppTodo/README.md` |

Rules:
- **Repeated work = check the runbook.** If you are about to do something you (or a prior session) have
  done before — especially device/build/observe loops — open `AppEggShellGallery/public-dev/docs/runbooks/`
  and use its commands and decision tree rather than improvising.
- **Tier 1 vs Tier 2 observation:** debug with raw `adb`/`simctl`/browser (fast, no setup); verify/gate
  with the `audit/` toolkit (`npm run observe -- …`, Appium/Playwright) for `testId` interaction,
  structured JSON, layout diffs, and CI. See `runbooks/index.md`.
- **When you discover a new gotcha or a runbook step is wrong/missing, update the doc** (append to
  `knowledge-base/engineering-log.md`; fix the relevant runbook) in the same change, so the next run
  benefits.
- If a runbook and live reality disagree (e.g. a path/flag changed), trust reality, fix it, and note it.
